          <GermlineClassification>Likely pathogenic</GermlineClassification>
          <Comment>The p.Asn78fs variant in HPS1 has not been previously reported in individuals with Hermansky-Pudlak syndrome but has been identified in 0.0009% (1/113770) of European (non-Finnish) chromosomes by the Genome Aggregation Database (gnomAD, http://gnomad.broadinstitute.org; dbSNP ID: rs773323079). Although this variant has been seen in the general population in a heterozygous state, its frequency is low enough to be consistent with a recessive carrier frequency. This variant has also been reported in ClinVar (Variation ID#: 435451) and has been interpreted as pathogenic by Invitae and Genetic Services Laboratory (University of Chicago). This variant is predicted to cause a frameshift, which alters the proteinâ€™s amino acid sequence beginning at position 78 and leads to a premature termination codon 43 amino acids downstream. This alteration is then predicted to lead to a truncated or absent protein. Loss of function of the HPS1 gene is an established disease mechanism in autosomal recessive Hermansky-Pudlak syndrome. In summary, although additional studies are required to fully establish its clinical significance, this variant is likely pathogenic for autosomal recessive Hermansky-Pudlak syndrome. ACMG/AMP Criteria applied: PVS1, PM2 (Richards 2015).</Comment>
